# Build Guide
This directory contains the full compiler toolchain, for devs building from source follow the instructions below.

## Prerequisites
- A c++20 or later compatible compiler (e.g. GCC 11+, Clang 13+, MSVC 19.29+)
- Python 3.10 or later
- Perl (on Linux/Mac only)
- Kairo Compiler v0.0.1-beta-26 or later

## Building the Toolchain
1. Clone the repository:
    ```bash
    git clone https://github.com/kairolang/kairo-lang
    cd kairo-lang
    ```

### For just building the toolchain:
2. Alias the build script for convenience (build.sh on Linux/Mac, build.bat on CMD and build.ps1 on PowerShell)
    ```bash
    # if you're on Linux/Mac alias it like this:
    alias hmake="./build.sh"

    # if you're on Windows CMD:
    doskey hmake=build.bat $*

    # if you're on Windows PowerShell:
    Set-Alias hmake .\build.ps1
    ```

3. Run the build script:
    ```bash
    hmake
    ```
This will compile the toolchain in the `build/{platform}/{release|debug}` directory.

### For testing a specific file that contains a `Test()` function:
2. Use the test script:
    ```bash
    # make sure to alias the build script first as shown above
    hmake test toolchain/Lexer/Lexer.kro
    ```
This will build and run the specified `fn Test() -> i32` function in the given file. It will error if the function is not found.

### If you have weird side effects where the code you've written is not being reflected in the build (using Kairo v0.0.1-x):
2. You can try to view the generated C++ code to debug:
    ```bash
    # make sure to alias the build script first as shown above
    hmake line toolchain/Lexer/Lexer.kro
    ```

3. You can also view a specific line or range of lines:
    ```bash
    # make sure to alias the build script first as shown above
    hmake line toolchain/Lexer/Lexer.kro 42         # view line 42
    hmake line toolchain/Lexer/Lexer.kro 10:20      # view lines 10 to 20
    ```

3. other kinds of issues can be debugged by extracting the compile command itself and then running it manually with a verbose flag:
    ```bash
    # make sure to alias the build script first as shown above
    hmake test toolchain/Lexer/Lexer.kro

    # outputs like so:
    [01/26/26 13:20:26] INFO     Copied test file to build/.shared/tests/Lexer.kro                                       build.py:346
                        INFO     Compiling build/.shared/tests/Lexer.kro with command: kairo                             build.py:200
                                 build/.shared/tests/Lexer.kro -obuild/.gens/test_run
                                 -I/Volumes/Foundry/kairo/kairo-lang -I/Volumes/Foundry/kairo/kairo-lang/toolchain
warn: variable 'frac_start' set but not used
   -->  at /Volumes/Foundry/kairo/kairo-lang/toolchain/Lexer/Immediate.kro:908:16
906 |                 idx = 0;
907 |
908 |                 var frac_start: usize = 0;
    :                 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
909 |                 var parsing_frac: bool = false;

warn: private field '_conflict_state' is not used
   -->  at /Volumes/Foundry/kairo/kairo-lang/build/.shared/tests/Lexer.kro:915:4
913 |     }
914 |
915 |     var _conflict_state: ConflictMarker = ConflictMarker::None;
    :     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
916 |
917 |     ///========= Lexical Parsing Functions ==========///

success: compilation successful
[01/26/26 13:20:36] INFO     Compiled build/.shared/tests/Lexer.kro successfully.                                    build.py:204
                    INFO     Running test binary build/.gens/test_run                                                build.py:361
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    
    # extract the command after "with command:" (removing the line breaks and log locations [build.py:XXX])
    # then run the command with `--verbose` flag like so:
    kairo build/.shared/tests/Lexer.kro -obuild/.gens/test_run -I/Volumes/Foundry/kairo/kairo-lang -I/Volumes/Foundry/kairo/kairo-lang/toolchain --verbose
    
    # this may give you more insight into what is going wrong.
    # NOTE: This command doesn't sync the source files before compiling, so if you've made changes you'll need to re-run the `hmake test <file>` command to sync them first.
    ```
